{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The traveling-salesman heuristic produces a route that is no more than 1.5x the length of the optimal route for inputs up to 20 stops.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Failure is in algorithmic quality at a single computation boundary (heuristic vs optimal baseline), with no required I/O. This is not inherently a module-wiring or external-infra failure.","test_description":"Run deterministic datasets (sizes 3..20), compute exact optimal tour length (e.g., Held-Karp/bruteforce for small n), run heuristic, and assert heuristic_length/optimal_length <= 1.5 for each case.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.75,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The delivery time window estimates are computed correctly from the distance between consecutive stops and the configured average speed for the road type.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure is likely at local module handoff: route segment distances + road-type speed config + estimator. A pure unit test of one formula can miss mapping/wiring errors between these modules.","test_description":"Wire real distance-segment objects, real road-type speed configuration, and estimator module; feed a multi-stop route with mixed road types and assert per-leg and total time windows match expected distance/speed calculations.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The shift-hours validator rejects a route whose total estimated time exceeds the driver's remaining shift hours, returning the excess amount.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is a local arithmetic/validation rule (compare estimated total vs remaining shift, compute excess). No external infra or cross-module boundary is required to expose the core failure.","test_description":"Call validator with representative totals and remaining-shift values (including boundary equality and fractional hours) and assert rejection plus exact excess amount when total > remaining.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.88,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When one address in the list fails geocoding (API returns no results), the service skips that stop and optimizes the remaining addresses, reporting which addresses were skipped.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Behavior crosses a real external API boundary. Mocked geocoding can hide contract/HTTP handling failures (empty-results payload shape, status handling, retries/timeouts) that affect skip-and-continue behavior.","test_description":"Execute end-to-end service call against a real geocoding endpoint (or provider sandbox) with one known unresolvable address and several resolvable ones; assert failed address is reported as skipped and final optimized route excludes it while including all resolvable stops.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.3,"System":0.62,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Duplicate addresses in the input list are consolidated into a single stop with combined delivery items, not visited twice.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real risk is interaction between deduplication/aggregation and route planning modules: duplicates must merge before optimization and produce one visited stop with combined payload.","test_description":"Run pipeline from input normalization through optimizer using duplicated addresses with distinct item payloads; assert one stop exists for that address, item lists are merged correctly, and route contains that stop exactly once.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Un